Task 2: Implement Basic RBAC Models in Linux
Subtask 2.1: Creating User Roles and Groups
Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) assigns permissions to roles rather than individual users. Let's create a basic RBAC structure:

# Create security-related groups
sudo groupadd security-admins
sudo groupadd security-analysts
sudo groupadd security-users

# Verify groups were created
grep -E "(security-admins|security-analysts|security-users)" /etc/group
Subtask 2.2: Creating Users for Different Roles
Create users representing different security roles:

# Create security administrator
sudo useradd -m -s /bin/bash -G security-admins sec-admin
sudo passwd sec-admin

# Create security analyst
sudo useradd -m -s /bin/bash -G security-analysts sec-analyst
sudo passwd sec-analyst

# Create regular security user
sudo useradd -m -s /bin/bash -G security-users sec-user
sudo passwd sec-user

# Verify users were created
tail -3 /etc/passwd
When prompted, set simple passwords like SecAdmin123, SecAnalyst123, and SecUser123 respectively.

Subtask 2.3: Setting Up Directory Structure with Permissions
Create a directory structure that reflects different security levels:

# Create security directories
sudo mkdir -p /opt/security/{admin,analyst,shared,logs}

# Set ownership and permissions
sudo chown root:security-admins /opt/security/admin
sudo chmod 750 /opt/security/admin

sudo chown root:security-analysts /opt/security/analyst
sudo chmod 750 /opt/security/analyst

sudo chown root:security-users /opt/security/shared
sudo chmod 755 /opt/security/shared

sudo chown root:security-admins /opt/security/logs
sudo chmod 740 /opt/security/logs

# Verify permissions
ls -la /opt/security/
